The company has been running a marketing campaign on their website, and they want to test the effectiveness of two different versions of their homepage (A and B) to determine which one leads to higher conversion rates. Your task is to design and analyze A/B tests to compare the performance of these two homepage versions. Here are the steps you can follow to design and analyze the A/B tests:

from scipy.stats import ttest_ind
from scipy import stats
version_a = df[df['Version'] == 'A']['OrderValue']
version_b = df[df['Version'] == 'B']['OrderValue']
t_stat, p_value = stats.ttest_ind(version_a, version_b, equal_var=False)
print('P-value:', t_stat)
if p_value < 0.05:
  print('We reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
  print('We fail to reject the null hypothesis.')
# The p-value is less than 0.05, so we reject the null hypothesis.

from scipy.stats import t
import numpy as np
def mean_confidence_interval(data, confidence=0.95):
  a = 1.0 * np.array(data)
  n = len(a)
  m, se = np.mean(a), stats.sem(a)
  h = se * t.ppf((1 + confidence) / 2., n-1)
  return m, m-h, m+h
mean_confidence_interval(version_a)
mean_confidence_interval(version_b)

Develop a script for scraping email addresses from a list of domains • Ensure the script can locate and extract information from the “Impressum” page of each domain, • Handle different variations of email addresses (@, [ät], at, and so on...) • Can extract the Email Address from an Image. (Sometimes webmaster paste the Email as a JPEG or PNG, to prevent scraping

In [ ]:
def extractTextFromImage(imagePath): # Processes images and extracts text using OCR
    image = Image.open(imagePath)             # Open image using image path
    text = pytesseract.image_to_string(image) # Convert image to text
    return text
In [ ]:
def extractEMAILS(text): # Extracts email addresses from text
    emails=[]
    emailREGEX=[r'\b\S+\[at\]\S+\b',r'\b\S+@\S+\b',r'\b\S+\s*@\s*\S',r'[\w.-]+\(a\)[\w.-]+'] #For [a], @, spaces @ , (a)
    for regex in emailREGEX:
        addresses = re.findall(regex, text)
        emails.extend(addresses)
    return emails
In [ ]:
def scrapeEmails(domain): # Scraps email addresses from a domain's Impressum page

    emailsExtracted = []
    url = "https://www."+str(domain)+"/impressum"

    try: #Try except clause used to handle errors

        response = requests.get(url)                        #Go to url
        soup = BeautifulSoup(response.text, 'html.parser')  #Parse

        text = soup.get_text()                              #convert to text form
        emailsExtracted.extend(extractEMAILS(text))         # Finds email addresses in text and add to list

         # Finds email addresses in images
        imageTags = soup.find_all('img')
        for imageTAG in imageTags:
                imageURL = imageTAG['src']
                if imageURL.endswith('.jpg') or imageURL.endswith('.jpeg') or imageURL.endswith('.png'):
                    # Processes the image
                    imageResponse = requests.get(imageURL)
                    imagePath = f"{domain}_image.jpg"  # Save the image locally
                    with open(imagePath, 'wb') as f:
                        f.write(imageResponse.content)
                    text = extractTextFromImage(imagePath)
                    emailsExtracted.extend(extractEMAILS(text))

    except requests.exceptions.RequestException as e:
            print("Error has occurred while accessing",url,"The Error is: ",str(e))

    return emailsExtracted

1.How has retail economic activity in the United States changed over the past five years?

In [ ]:
# 1) How has retail economic activity in the United States changed over the past five years?

#Seperating & Combining only relevant data for Q1 i.e all sales column and year column:
salesCOLS = [col for col in df.columns if col.startswith('data.sales')]   #Extracting  relevant sales column names
dataQ1 = df[['time.year'] + salesCOLS].copy()                             #Saving data from relevant columns

dataQ1=dataQ1.loc[dataQ1['time.year']>=2012]                                #As we want to compare of only past 5 years


yearlySales = dataQ1.groupby('time.year')[salesCOLS].sum()                  #Calculating yearly sales:

# Visualizing Results:
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
for col in salesCOLS:
    plt.plot(yearlySales.index, yearlySales[col], label=col.split('.')[-1])

plt.xlabel('Year')
plt.ylabel('Total Sales')
plt.title('Retail Economic Activity in the United States')
plt.legend()
plt.show()

traditional=dataq4.groupby('quarter')['data.sales.retail trade'].sum()
# converting the period index to a numeric representation

traditional.index = traditional.index.to_timestamp()
